        "## 15. Reflection Questions\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ZO_CI2cWS5FK"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.1 Problem Formulation\n",
        "\n",
        "**What is a state in this lab?**\n",
        "\n",
        "the state is basically where the drone is on the map. like if the drone is at row 2 column 3 we write it as (2,3). thats it\n",
        "\n",
        "**What is an action?**\n",
        "\n",
        "An action is a direction the drone can take or move. we have four actions: UP, DOWN, LEFT and RIGHT.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What does the result function do?**\n",
        "\n",
        "The result function looks at where you are now and the move you want to make. Then it tells you your new position after the move.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why is it useful to separate the problem from the algorithm?**\n",
        "\n",
        "If the map changes, you do not need to change BFS or DFS. These algorithms work on any problem with the same structure. They are not made only for drones or grids."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "y8creWSsS7gT"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.2 Breadth-First Search (BFS)\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why does BFS use a FIFO queue?**\n",
        "\n",
        "let me put it in this way We want to visit all nodes that are 1 step away first. Then we visit all nodes that are 2 steps away, and then all nodes that are 3 steps away. A queue helps us do this. New nodes are added to the back of the queue, and nodes are removed from the front. This means the oldest nodes are visited first.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why does BFS find the shortest path?**\n",
        "\n",
        "It find the shortest path Because it is explored  level by level. The first time it reaches the goal it taken automatically the fewest steps possible.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What role does the reached set play?**\n",
        "\n",
        "The reached set keeps track of all the states that have already been visited.\n",
        "Before visiting a new state, BFS checks if it is already in the reached set. If it is, BFS skips it.\n",
        "This prevents the drone from visiting the same place again and again. Without the reached set, BFS will get stuck in a loop and run forever."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "fpnc8tm9VyiB"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.3 Depth-First Search (DFS)\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why does DFS use a stack?**\n",
        "\n",
        "DFS  use a stack Because we  want  always to  dicover the most recently first node that has been added .OR we know a stack removes from the top so DFS goes as deep as possible before trying other branches.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Is DFS guaranteed to find the shortest path?**\n",
        "\n",
        "No. DFS can find a long winding path before finding the short one.The goal  It just  to finds a path, not necessarily the best one.\n",
        "\n",
        "**When can DFS use less memory than BFS?**\n",
        "\n",
        "DFS use less memory When the solution is very deep in the tree. because BFS has to store all nodes at the current level which can be huge. DFS only stores one path at a time not more.\n",
        "\n",
        "**When can DFS perform badly?**\n",
        "\n",
        "it can perform badly when the search space is very deep or infinite. DFS can go down and use a very long wrong branch and waste a lot of time for nothing  before backtracking."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Ba5bZshoYLKD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.4 Depth-Limited Search (DLS)\n",
        "\n",
        "**What happens when the depth limit is too small?**\n",
        "\n",
        "DLS returns cutoff which means it stopped before finding the goal. It does not mean there is no solution, just that the limit was too small.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What is the meaning of cutoff?**\n",
        "\n",
        "Cutoff means the search hit the depth limit before finding the goal or proving there is no solution. It is different from failure which means no solution exists at all.\n",
        "\n",
        "**How is DLS different from DFS?**\n",
        "\n",
        "DLS is DFS with a maximum depth. Once a node reaches the limit DLS stops going deeper and backtracks.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why do we use path-cycle checking in DLS?**\n",
        "\n",
        "Because DLS explores the same states at different depth limits on purpose, so a global reached set would block valid paths. Path checking only avoids loops on the current path."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "S2jUPNM3WgCl"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.5 Iterative Deepening Search (IDS)\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why does IDS repeat DLS with increasing limits?**\n",
        "\n",
        "hmmm Because we dont know in advance how deep the solution is. But by  starting at 0 and increasing by 1 each time we are guaranteed to find the shallowest solution eventually.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why can IDS be complete even though DLS with a small limit is not?**\n",
        "\n",
        "As IDS keeps increasing the limit until it either finds the goal or proves it does not exist. A single DLS run with a small limit is incomplete but IDS never stops until it finds the answer.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why does IDS use less memory than BFS?**\n",
        " at any point IDS only keeps one path in memory just like DFS. BFS has to store all nodes at the current frontier level.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What is the cost of repeating the search from the root?**\n",
        "\n",
        "IDS re-expands nodes from earlier levels many times. But most of the work happens at the deepest level so the total extra cost is not that bad."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "TxCvqxYmXqMC"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## 15.6 Real-World Drone Context\n",
        "\n",
        "**What might make one route safer or more practical?**\n",
        "\n",
        "In life the drone might need to avoid trees, water bodies, restricted airspace, or areas with strong wind. A shorter path on the grid might still be dangerous in practice.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Which algorithm for fewest moves?**\n",
        "\n",
        "I will choose BFS because it explores level by level and always returns the shortest path when all moves cost the same.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Which algorithm for limiting search depth?**\n",
        "\n",
        "I will choose DLS because it stops searching beyond a set depth. This is useful if the drone has a battery limit and cannot afford to explore too far.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What limitations does this grid model have?**\n",
        "\n",
        "The grid is too simple.The Real drone navigation has to deal with diagonal movement, altitude changes, wind speed, GPS errors, battery life, and obstacles that move. A flat 2D grid with equal step costs can not capture all of this."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "obAz7oOqX8gw"
      }
    },
